    "summary": "Naram-Sin of Akkad, who reigned approximately 2254–2218 BC, was the grandson of [[event:1722|Sargon of Akkad]] and the most powerful ruler of the [[event:45|Akkadian Empire]]. He extended the empire to its greatest territorial extent, conducting successful military campaigns from the Persian Gulf to the Taurus Mountains in Anatolia, and became the first Mesopotamian ruler known to have claimed divine status during his own lifetime, adopting the title 'God of Akkad' and adding a divine determinative (the cuneiform sign for deity) before his own name.\n\nNaram-Sin's deification was a revolutionary political innovation. In claiming to be a living god rather than merely a king favoured by the gods, he radically transformed the ideological basis of Mesopotamian kingship. This claim is commemorated on the Victory Stele of Naram-Sin, a masterpiece of ancient art now in the Louvre, which depicts him striding up a mountain in a horned helmet (a divine symbol) while defeated enemies fall at his feet. The stele's artistic innovations — depicting the scene on a diagonal plane rather than in the traditional horizontal registers — make it one of the most sophisticated works of ancient Near Eastern art.\n\nDespite his military successes, ancient Mesopotamian tradition remembered Naram-Sin as a ruler whose hubris brought divine punishment upon his land. The Curse of Akkad, a Sumerian literary composition composed after the empire's fall, attributed the destruction of Akkad to Naram-Sin's alleged sacrilege against the temple of Enlil at Nippur. Whether or not this reflects historical events, it illustrates how later generations processed the dramatic collapse of the empire that followed his reign, a collapse associated in part with the [[event:1795|4.2 Kiloyear Event]] climatic disruption.",
